Layout Page
Purpose: Defines a consistent structure (header, footer, navigation) across multiple views.

Analogy: Think of it like a master template in Word or PowerPoint—every page inherits the same design.

Usage:

Declared in _ViewStart.cshtml or directly in a view using Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_Layout.cshtml";

Contains @RenderBody() → placeholder for the main content of each view.

Can also have @RenderSection("scripts", required: false) for optional sections.

Benefit: Avoids duplication, ensures consistent look and feel.

Partial View
Purpose: Reusable view component for rendering small chunks of UI (like widgets, forms, menus).

Analogy: Like a Lego block you can plug into different pages.

Usage:

Created as .cshtml file, often stored in Views/Shared.

Rendered using @Html.Partial("_MyPartial"), @Html.RenderPartial("_MyPartial"), or @Html.Action("ActionName").

Benefit: Promotes modularity, reusability, and cleaner code.

Key Difference
Feature	Layout Page	Partial View
Scope	Whole page template	Small reusable section
Placeholder	@RenderBody() / @RenderSection()	Rendered via Html.Partial
Purpose	Consistency across views	Reusability of components
Analogy	Master template	Lego block

⚡ 20 Quick Q&A Practice
Q: What is a Layout Page in ASP.NET MVC?
A: A master template that defines common structure (header, footer, nav) for multiple views.

Q: Which file often sets the layout for all views?
A: _ViewStart.cshtml.

Q: What placeholder is used in Layout Page for main content?
A: @RenderBody().

Q: How do you define optional sections in Layout Page?
A: Using @RenderSection("name", required: false).

Q: What is a Partial View?
A: A reusable view component for rendering small sections of UI.

Q: How do you render a partial view in Razor?
A: @Html.Partial("_PartialName").

Q: Difference between Html.Partial and Html.RenderPartial?
A: Html.Partial returns MvcHtmlString; Html.RenderPartial writes directly to response (faster).

Q: Can a partial view have its own layout?
A: No, partial views don’t use layouts.

Q: Where are layout pages usually stored?
A: Views/Shared folder.

Q: Where are partial views usually stored?
A: Views/Shared or inside specific controller folders.

Q: What is the benefit of using Layout Pages?
A: Consistency and reduced duplication across views.

Q: What is the benefit of using Partial Views?
A: Reusability and modular design.

Q: Can you nest partial views inside other partial views?
A: Yes, partial views can be nested.

Q: Which directive sets layout in a view?
A: Layout = "~/Views/Shared/_Layout.cshtml";.

Q: Which method allows rendering a partial view via controller action?
A: @Html.Action("ActionName").

Q: What happens if you don’t specify a layout?
A: The view renders standalone without shared structure.

Q: Can layout pages contain scripts and styles?
A: Yes, typically in <head> and @RenderSection("scripts").

Q: What is _ViewImports.cshtml used for?
A: To import namespaces and tag helpers globally.

Q: Can partial views accept a model?
A: Yes, they can be strongly typed.

Q: One-line difference between Layout and Partial View?
A: Layout = whole page template; Partial = reusable component.
